<p>a job to stop the Battalion from following him, however they got all in the train at last &amp; off we went, they still fought in the carriages, I never laughed so much in my life as I laughed that night, it was better than a pantomime, on the way down 2 or 3 fellows fell out I don't know what became of them, we did not know where they were going to take us, although we heard some talk of Tel el Kebir when day light came we could see we were not bound for Cairo for on one side of us was nothing but the bare &amp; sandy desert &amp; the other side all beautiful</p>
